Train

If you need some quick instructions on how to play the game, expecially if you have never played an interactive fiction game before, type "help" at any time.

You don't even remember what happened. As you come too, you are standing in a compartment on a train, with your jacket in your hand. You quickly look around, still dizzy. The train is moving. Outside the window, you can see a densely forested area roll by. You can hear someone walking outside the compartment door. You breathe in and out and swallow one or two times. When your head stops spinning, you find something unexpected and very nasty at your feet.
This is a rather nice and clean compartment on a train. There is a seat here, which is convertible into a bed, as well as a small table. The window is on the northern side of the compartment.
You can go south or out.
You can see a body.
> x body

> x body
The man is clearly dead. He is not breathing, and blood has trickled down his cheek from both his mouth and one of his ears. He is badly bruised, and a cut-wound is clearly visible on his stomach. He is a dark-haired but balding middle aged man, whom you do not recognize. He is dressed in a suit, smeared with blood.
on him is a document.
> search body

> search body
You quickly search the body. You find a small document, which you put in your pocket.
> open window

> open window
You open it.
> take body

> take body
You bend down and put both of you arms under the man. With a  strength you didn't know you had, you barely manage to lift the man.
> throw out body

> throw out body
You do that, and hear a soft sound as the ground is hit.
> throw out jacket

> throw out jacket
You do that, and hear a soft sound as the ground is hit.
> take note

> take note
I can't see that.
> read note

> read note
I can't see that. (note)
Somebody slides a note under the door.
> s

> s

You are standing outside compartment number 1 (which is "your" compartment) at one end of a train wagon, with the door to the next wagon to your west. There are more compartments than yours, but they do not seem important to you. Their numbers are 2 and 3. The wagon continues to the east, where there are more compartments, and your compartment is to the north of here. The walls are panelled with wood, and the floor is carpeted in a pleasant blue-green color.
You can go north, east or west.
> e

> e

Your are standing in the back end of the wagon which contains your compartment, which faces east. There are several compartments in sight, but none currently seems interesting. The compartments in your immediate vicinity are number 4 to 7. The carpeted floor is does not make a sound when you step upon it. To the east of you is the door to the next wagon.
You can go west or east.
> e

> e

You are standing at the western end of the train wagon behind the one with "your" compartment, with the door to that wagon to your west. There are several compartments here, but most seem uninteresting. They number 8 to 10, withnumber 11 to 14 a bit to the east. The wagon continues to the east, and the floor is carpeted in an emotional, ruby red color.
You can go west or east.
> e

> e

You are standing at the eastern end of the train wagon behind the one with "your" compartment, with the door to that wagon to your west. There are several compartments here, but most seem uninteresting. They number 11 to 14, with number 14 the furthest to the east. Further to the west, there are more compartments. The wagon continues to the west, and the floor is carpeted in an emotional, ruby red color. To the east is a door with a sign.
You can go west or east.
> enter compartment 14

> enter compartment 14

The compartment looks like yours, only a bit bigger. Also, the carpeting and seat is another color.
You can go southwest or out.
The moment you step into the compartment, someone takes hold of your arms and prevents you from moving. You are essentially stuck and cannot pull loose.
"Sorry, but safety comes first."
A grey-haired man in a matching suit stands upp and examines you with his eyes. You do not have time to answer before he continues, looking the man behind you in the eyes.
"Let go."
The grip holdning your hands in place loosens, and for the first time you can see the man behind you. Although almost as old looking as the grey-haired man, he is much stronger than you.
"We have met before, although you... might not remember me. We are colleagues, one could say."
What do you say?
1: Who are you?
2: What do you want?
3: Who am I?
> 3
You ask the man who you are.
"We do not have time to discuss such things right now, but you need to know that we are working together."

"In short, I am sure that you realise that you are in trouble. That is to say, WE are in trouble. Do not worry; we are on the same side. I know about what happened in you compartment. Nevertheless, we must continue."
The man lights a cigarette.
"The man we are after is in the restaurant car having dinner as we speak. I do not think he will recognize you, although I wonder about his "friends". We need you to eavesdrop. It is of greatest importance that we catch everything they might say if we are to be successful."
He pauses for a moment, but makes it clear with his eyes that you should keep quiet.
"You will use a small tape recorder and record what is said. All you need to do is to enter the luggage car at the back of the train and find the red box marked with "Svi-Air 505". In it is the recorder. We have had to stash it this way to avoid it being found in the customs. You will open it with this key."
The man hands you a small key.
"The people you are looking for will sooner or later be sitting at table 7. You need to place the recorder there before they get there. And remember: It needs to be turned on. When you have recorded something interesting, come back. And hurry up."
Before you can reply, the bald man opens the compartment door and gently pushes you out.

You are standing at the eastern end of the train wagon behind the one with "your" compartment, with the door to that wagon to your west. There are several compartments here, but most seem uninteresting. They number 11 to 14, with number 14 the furthest to the east. Further to the west, there are more compartments. The wagon continues to the west, and the floor is carpeted in an emotional, ruby red color. To the east is a door with a sign.
You can go west or east.
> e

> e

You are at the very front of the luggage car, at the back of the train. It lacks windows, but is dimly lit by a small lamp in the ceiling. A net of wires with a door, which go almost up to the ceiling, separate this part of the car from the main part. There is a small wooden chair here. A compartment door is on the northern wall.
You can go west.
> stand on chair

> stand on chair
You stand up on the chair. From here, you can reach the ceiling and the top of the net of wires.
> climb wires

> climb wires
You reach for the top of the wires and get a good grip. You put you foot between a few of them. Almost scratching your arm, you still manage to squeeze through and almost fall down on the other side of the wires.

You are in the main area of the luggage car. The exit to the passanger cars is to the west, and on the other side of a net of wires. The car is just dimly lit, propably by a small bulb somewhere. The luggage area is not particulary big, and ends with a wall of metal to the east, where there is also a metal hatch (it is a bit too small to be called a door).
There are a lot of nondescript things here, but mostly there is a huge pile of boxes of various shapes, sizes and colors.

You can see a hatch.
> x boxes

> x boxes
You examine the pile of boxes, and something cathes your eye. The text "Svi-Air 505" can be seen on a light red box under a few other boxes. Moving the other boxes slightly lets you pull the Svi-Air 505-box out onto the floor in front of you.
> open red box

> open red box
You unlock the red box, and open the lid.
> x red box

> x red box
The box is rather big and heavy. It is light red, and the text "Svi-Air 505" is clearly visible on the lid.
It contains a tape recorder.
> take tape recorder

> take tape recorder
You pick it up.
> x tape recorder

> x tape recorder
It is a small tape recorder. You could easily conceal it in your pocket; it is in fact so small that it would be possible to miss it if it was laying right in front of you. You do not know exactly how it works, and its techincal appearance makes it hard for you to make sense of it. You do note, however, that there is no "Play"-button. Still, itb has a button saying "Rec.".
> press button

> press button
You start the tape recorder.
> kick hatch

> kick hatch
You kick the hatch. With a loud noise, it seems to crumble somewhat and slowly swings open.
> enter hatch

> enter hatch
You crawl through the hatch.

You find yourself in a small area which can barely be called a "room" behind an open hatch (which cannot be reached from the inside). Light enters the area through the hatch. The walls are made of metal, and it looks almost like you imagine being inside an air vent looks, although a bit bigger. There is a small grating on the eastern "wall", leading out of the train. You can feel the wind from the outside.
You can go out, west or east.
> pull grating

> pull grating
You manage to pull the grating loose. Almost falling on your back (only prevented by you not standing up), you lie there with a piece of the grating in your hand.
> w

> w

You are in the main area of the luggage car. The exit to the passanger cars is to the west, and on the other side of a net of wires. The car is just dimly lit, propably by a small bulb somewhere. The luggage area is not particulary big, and ends with a wall of metal to the east, where there is also a metal hatch (it is a bit too small to be called a door).
There are a lot of nondescript things here, but mostly there is a huge pile of boxes of various shapes, sizes and colors.

You can see a hatch and a red box.
> cut wires

> cut wires
You cut the net open with the sharp end of the piece of grating. When you are finished, there is a hole big enough for you to pass through.
> w

> w

You are at the very front of the luggage car, at the back of the train. It lacks windows, but is dimly lit by a small lamp in the ceiling. A net of wires with a door, which go almost up to the ceiling, separate this part of the car from the main part. There is a small wooden chair here. A compartment door is on the northern wall.
You can go west.
A man walks into the luggage car from the front.
"Um Gott's.... what in heaven's name are you doing?"
The man speaks in a lightly broken English. He looks obviously chocked, like he's never seen a suspicous passanger in the wrong car beore. He quickly finds himself. Quickly looking back over his shoulder, as if he wanted to know you where alone, he continues:
"I don't know what you are up to, but I have a family and christmas is coming... I guess."
You instantly realize what he is talking about.
"I will not report this for... say... 50 $. In cash."
This seems a little steep.
What do you say?
1: Sure!
2: Maybe... 30 will do?
3: No way.
> 1
"Sure!", you say, while reaching for your wallet. You pull out 50 dollars.
The man smiles slightly while pocketing your money.
"A pleasure doing business with you.", he says.
He quickly disappears back to where he came from.

