> z
Time passes.
The man re-enters the room, once again closing the door behind him.

"I'm glad that you are still here. I just needed to make sure I still have a way out."

He sighs.

"As I told you, you fucked this up good. Of course, you did a lot of what you were supposed to. For me, this was supposed to be the last mission. It was for you as well, but it was supposed to end another way."

He sits down on the desk, entirely this time.

"We had this planned quite well, me and the...commander. Yes, you will still not know his name. There were five of us. You know me and the commander. You also - most probably - still know yourself in spite of the damage you might have... been caused. You killed Frank just like you were supposed to. Thrilling for the commander. Getting rid of Frank, a double agent, and getting the mission done at the same time. You might, or might not, have known that Frank was you ally. You were going to take the fall for killing Frank and undoubtedly be blamed for the leak in intelligence as well. At the same time, your... people... would not be able to help you. Not here. "

He now seems entirely calm.

"...and the three of us who made it out would have done a man's job. However, both you and I know this will not last. It's quite clear which side is winning and which side history will dig in. I however, am not bound by any loyalty. I'm a pragmatist, as allways. But stopping us...well, you... I would not be called a defector but a hero. That would have been my way out. And you... I would be sure to tell them how you had switched sides once again. They would believe me. Why else would you kill your ally?"

He stands up and takes a few steps and stops again, standing a few feet from you.

"But you had to survive. You had to stop me. Ironic, that liquor finally saves a life; especially in your case. However, as you probably relize, it is by no means permanent. Anyway, your escape on the train is what attracted the police. They had to find the body at once. They had to question the passengers. They had to talk to the idiot who remembered me coming out of the compartment after your little drink.The one who remembered seing you enter earlier, when you talked to me and the commander before we boarded the train. If not for a lot of things, I could have turned that recorder in to the authorities and seemingly foil your plan. Your death would have been forgiven, but as things stand now I would probably have a date with the hangman."

He is now right next to you and lowers his voice almost to a whisper.

"But I'm not going alone. Even if I do not win, you will certainly not make it out alive either. I, for one, am not terribly upset by this outcome. Being foiled by you would have been one thing, but... unforeseen circumstances? These things happen."

The bald man pulls out a gun.

As the man pushes you and the chair down backwards, your leg comes free.
> kick man

> kick man
You can just about reach him  with a weak kick. If not for the surprise, he might not have felt anything at all.

As it is, it is enough to make him stumple and try to return the favour. He misses, instead hitting the back of the chair.

It breaks, and suddently, you are free. You get up on your feet and push the man to the side. He drops the gun. You have switched sides. The desk is behind you, while the man stands by the broken chair.

The bald man still has one gun more than you. It has fallen to the floor, but he is picking it up which might give you a moment.

You are in a quite small, dark room. This little office, with the curtains drawn, contains a desk in front of a bookcase. On the desk is a large, heavy paperweight. On the floor is a thick rug, with your chair on it. You are tied to the chair and cannot move.
You can see a wooden desk and a man.
> take paperweight

> take paperweight
You take the large and heavy paperweight, which is in the shape of an eagle, and hold it in your hand.
The bald man has the gun in his hand once again, pointed right at you. You have the desk behind your back, with the man in front of you.
> throw paperweight

> throw paperweight
The gun is pointed directly at you.

As you throw the paperweight, the man is caught by surprise. His shot misses you and ends up somewhere among the old books in the bookcase behind you. The paperweight, shaped like an eagle, makes one last flight.

The bald man is not quick enough, and the paperweight hits him right on the head. One of the corners pierces his skin and the blood begins pouring. He falls to the floor. You quickly notice that he is hurt very badly, to which you woud not object. Blood pours from his head, onto the rug. You can hear the man breathing, but he is unconscious.

The gun lies right beside the man.

You contemplate ending his life, but it looks like no intervention from you is needed. You think about calling this in; contacting the police. You do not even speak the local language. What would a phonecall accomplish, aside from proving the man right? Nobody would believe your story if they would even listen.

Who are you, and who is he? Should you have remembered what he was speaking about, as he seemed to assume? Is there someone you should contact, someone who could help you out?

You sit down at the desk for a moment, thinking about what to do. As you open the drawer, you find a similar tape recorder with the tape still in it. You look at it for a while. Before leaving, you pick up the bloody paperweight. You set it down on the tape recorder heavily, crushing it. Keeping the tape would not help, especially if it was true that you were working against the people you have been dealing with in the last 24 hours.

You open the office door and find yourself in an empty hallway. The street door is just down the stairs, and you walk into a chilly night. What you will do is uncertain, but perhaps someone, somewhere will know.

As for now, you walk away to find somewhere to spend the night. Perhaps you have even deserved a drink after stopping whatever this was. You hail the next taxi you see and call this a night.
[state=Finished]
